					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Memblers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">another possibility is to change that movement_speed to be a table and use an index register during the ADCs to select from some pre-defined speeds.</div>
<br />Or you could make "speed" a variable and perform some math on it. Often when I implement movement, the keys act on the speed variable (as opposed to the player's position). The right key would increase the value of "speed" (until a max positive value) and the right key would decrease it (until a min negative value). When neither is pressed, it's progressively forced toward 0. And "speed" is always (every frame) added to the player's coordinates.
<br />
<br />This adds a nice acceleration and inertia effect to the game. I often have acceleration on the Y axis too, wich means that all you have to do to jump is place a way high value on "speedY". No floor under the player causes "speedY" to increase (until a max positive value), simulating gravity (wich is what brings you down after a jump). If you find good values for the step you use to increment/decrement and the max/min values, it can look and feel very nice.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

